 val cell=build("biology-cell-explorer",AuthoredExperienceCopy("Cell biology · Cell structure and organelles","A layered plant/animal cell connects selectable organelles to functions, availability, and labelled structure.",listOf("cells as basic units of life"),"Cell structures work as a coordinated system. The nucleus stores DNA, ribosomes build polypeptides, mitochondria transfer energy, and the selectively permeable membrane regulates exchange. Plant cells additionally show chloroplasts and a large vacuole in this comparison.","A diagram's organelle size and position are schematic; function should not be inferred from drawing size.","Selecting a mitochondrion reveals its role in aerobic respiration while retaining its location in the cell context.","Which selected structures disappear when switching from the plant comparison to animal?","The chloroplast and large central vacuole are flagged absent; shared structures remain.","Plant cells have mitochondria but animal cells do not.","Select mitochondrion, switch cell type, and compare availability.","Both plant and animal cells use mitochondria for aerobic respiration.","Name the structure that contains DNA and coordinates gene expression.","Nucleus","The nucleus contains the main genomic DNA in these eukaryotic cell models.","Identify a structure by both location and function, while remembering the diagram is not to scale.","nucleus",listOf(v("part","selected organelle","","organelle","focus")),comparisonLabels="plant cell" to "animal cell"))
 val membrane=build("biology-membrane-transport",AuthoredExperienceCopy("Cell biology · Membrane transport","A two-compartment membrane model separates concentration-gradient-driven passive flux from an energy-dependent outward pump proxy.",listOf("concentration","cell membrane"),"Passive net transport follows an electrochemical or concentration gradient when the membrane is permeable. Active transport uses cellular energy and specific proteins, allowing movement that can oppose a gradient.","At dynamic equilibrium, particles still move both ways; only the net flux is approximately zero.","With outside concentration 80, inside 20, and positive permeability, passive net movement is inward.","Can the active pump make net movement outward even when passive movement is inward?","Yes, if its outward contribution exceeds the passive inward flux in this simplified model.","Equilibrium means particles stop moving.","Set equal concentrations and interpret zero net flux as a balance of opposing microscopic movement.","Zero net transport does not imply zero molecular motion.","Predict passive direction for outside 10 and inside 60.","Outward","Passive net movement follows the higher-to-lower concentration direction.","Separate passive and active contributions before naming the net direction.","membrane",listOf(v("Cout","outside concentration","relative concentration","outside","gradient input"),v("Cin","inside concentration","relative concentration","inside","gradient input"),v("J","net flux","relative flux","membrane","signed output")),comparisonLabels="passive transport" to "active transport"))
 val division=build("biology-cell-division",AuthoredExperienceCopy("Cell division · Mitosis and meiosis","A stage-controlled chromosome model compares one mitotic division with two meiotic divisions and their outcomes.",listOf("chromosomes","DNA replication"),"DNA replicates once before either process. Mitosis separates sister chromatids through one division and usually preserves chromosome-set number. Meiosis separates homologous chromosomes before sister chromatids and produces four haploid products after two divisions.","Chromosome number is counted by centromeres; replicated DNA does not automatically mean twice the chromosome number.","Starting with two homologous pairs, the simplified mitosis outcome has two diploid cells, while meiosis has four haploid cells.","Which process reduces chromosome-set number, and when is that visible?","Meiosis; reduction follows separation of homologous chromosomes in the first meiotic division.","Meiosis is simply mitosis performed twice.","Compare outcomes and note that homologues pair and separate in meiosis I, unlike mitosis.","The order and identity of what separates differ, enabling reduction and genetic variation.","How many daughter products follow one complete meiosis in this model?","Four haploid products","One DNA replication is followed by two divisions.","Mitosis supports continuity; meiosis changes ploidy and supports sexual reproduction.","chromosomes",listOf(v("n","chromosome-set number","sets","chromosomes","preserved or halved")),listOf(p("prophase","nucleus","replicated chromosomes","condense and organise division structures","visible chromosomes","Condensation permits organised movement.","Replication occurs before, not during, this stage."),p("metaphase","cell equator","condensed chromosomes","align with spindle attachments","ordered alignment","Attachment supports accurate separation.","Mitosis and meiosis I align different chromosome relationships."),p("anaphase","spindle","attached chromosomes","separate chromatids or homologues","two chromosome groups","The separated units depend on the process.","Do not treat homologues and sister chromatids as synonyms."),p("cytokinesis","cell boundary","separated nuclear material","partition cytoplasm","daughter cells","Physical division completes the cellular outcome.","Nuclear division and cytokinesis are related but distinct.")),"mitosis" to "meiosis"))
 val circulation=build("biology-circulation",AuthoredExperienceCopy("Human physiology · Heart and circulation","A step-linked double-circulation pathway connects heart chambers and vessels to cardiac output.",listOf("heart chambers","blood vessels","multiplication"),"The right heart sends blood through pulmonary circulation to the lungs. The left heart sends blood through systemic circulation to body tissues. Cardiac output is heart rate multiplied by stroke volume.","Arteries carry blood away from the heart and veins toward it; oxygen content is not the defining rule.","At 72 beats/min and 70 mL/beat, cardiac output is about 5.04 L/min.","If heart rate rises while stroke volume stays fixed, what happens to calculated cardiac output?","It rises proportionally in this model; this calculation is educational, not a health diagnosis.","All arteries carry oxygen-rich blood.","Trace the pulmonary artery and pulmonary veins while reading direction and gas-exchange labels.","The pulmonary artery carries blood away from the heart toward lungs; vessel direction defines artery/vein.","Calculate output at 100 beats/min and 80 mL/beat.","8 L/min","100×80=8000 mL/min=8 L/min.","Trace direction first, then interpret oxygenation and quantitative flow.","right-atrium",listOf(v("HR","heart rate","beats/min","heartRate","direct"),v("SV","stroke volume","mL/beat","strokeVolume","direct"),v("CO","cardiac output","L/min","body","product")),listOf(p("right-heart","right atrium and ventricle","systemic venous blood","receive then pump through pulmonary artery","blood sent to lungs","Pressure generated by the right ventricle drives pulmonary flow.","Artery means away from heart, not always oxygen-rich."),p("lungs","pulmonary capillaries","incoming blood and alveolar gases","exchange oxygen and carbon dioxide","oxygenated pulmonary venous blood","Diffusion follows partial-pressure gradients.","Blood is not converted into oxygen."),p("left-heart","left atrium and ventricle","pulmonary venous blood","receive then pump through aorta","systemic arterial flow","The thicker left ventricle supports systemic pressure.","Both sides pump the same long-term flow in a closed circulation.")),"pulmonary circulation" to "systemic circulation"))
 val genetics=build("biology-mendelian-genetics",AuthoredExperienceCopy("Genetics · Mendelian inheritance","A gamete-and-Punnett model separates genotype probabilities from phenotype probabilities under stated dominance assumptions.",listOf("alleles","fractions","gametes"),"Each gamete carries one allele for the modeled locus. Multiplying parental gamete probabilities fills genotype cells; phenotype probabilities then depend on the explicitly chosen dominance model.","Dominant means expressed in a heterozygote, not common, stronger, or better.","Aa×Aa gives genotype probabilities 1/4 AA, 1/2 Aa, 1/4 aa and, with complete A dominance, phenotype probability 3/4 A.","Does a 3:1 probability mean every family of four has exactly three dominant phenotypes?","No. It describes repeated independent outcomes under model assumptions, not a guaranteed small-family count.","A dominant allele must be the most common allele.","Set a dominant phenotype model while varying parental allele probabilities; compare dominance with resulting frequency.","Dominance describes genotype-to-phenotype expression and does not determine population frequency.","What genotype probabilities result from Aa×aa?","1/2 Aa and 1/2 aa","The heterozygous parent supplies A or a equally; the aa parent supplies only a.","State inheritance assumptions and keep genotype, phenotype, dominance, and frequency distinct.","punnett",listOf(v("P(A)₁","parent-one A gamete probability","probability","gametes1","input"),v("P(A)₂","parent-two A gamete probability","probability","gametes2","input"),v("P(genotype)","offspring genotype probability","probability","punnett","product and sum")),comparisonLabels="genotype distribution" to "phenotype distribution"))
